<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Under the proposed regulations, the tax consequences of callable preferred stock are intended to reflect the economic
expectations of the parties and to afford issuers flexibility to issue stock on terms that reflect their business
needs. The proposed regulations are also intended to foreclose corporations from attempting to use issuer calls
to create constructive distributions solely for tax planning reasons. However, no inference is to be drawn from the
proposed regulations as to the appropriate treatment of such call rights under current law. Such provisions are subject
to scrutiny under general tax principles (e.g., substance over form). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
De minimis exception. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Proposed &sect;1.305&hyph;5(b)(1) would replace the ``reasonable redemption premium'' exception under current
&sect;1.305&hyph;5(b)(2) with the statutory de minimis rule under section 305(c)(1) for mandatorily redeemable
and puttable stock, and extend the statutory rule to issuer calls. Extending this rule to issuer calls differs from
the treatment discussed in the legislative history of the 1990 Act, but is appropriate because the proposed regulations
limit constructive distribution treatment with respect to issuer calls to circumstances in which the stock is economically
similar to mandatorily redeemable stock. In those cases, the call premium cannot fairly be said to be ``in the nature
of a penalty for premature redemption.'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Since those cases are outside of the intended scope of the exception in the current regulations, there is no reason
to retain current &sect;1.305&hyph;5(b)(2) for callable stock. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Conforming changes. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The proposed regulations would conform the examples in &sect;&sect;1.305&hyph;3 and 1.305&hyph;5 to the proposed
changes described above. In addition, the proposed regulations would conform language in &sect;1.305&hyph;7(a)
to the proposed changes described above. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Effective dates. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Proposed &sect;1.305&hyph;5(b)(6) contains the effective date rules. In general, the regulations are proposed
to apply to stock issued on or after the date final regulations are filed with the 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=4 -->
Federal Register
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The committee reports to the 1990 Act indicate that Congress did not intend to limit the authority of the Secretary
to promulgate regulations relating to the accrual of redemption premiums on callable preferred stock. However,
the reports indicate that Congress anticipated any such regulations would be prospective. H.R. Conf. Rep. No. 964,
101st Cong., 2d Sess. 1095 (1990). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Although the proposed regulations do not apply to stock issued before the date final regulations are filed with the

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=4 -->
Federal Register
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
, the rules of sections 305(c) (1), (2), and (3) apply to stock described therein issued on or after October 10, 1990,
except as provided in section 11322(b)(2) of the 1990 Act. The committee reports to the 1990 Act express Congress'
intention that the economic accrual and OID de minimis rules generally apply as of the effective date of the 1990 Act
without regard to when regulations are amended to reflect such rules. H.R. Conf. Rep. No. 964, 101st Cong., 2d Sess.
1095 (1990). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The committee reports note that, in general, the OID de minimis rule will not apply to preferred stock that is callable
solely at the option of the issuer (unless such stock is subject to a mandatory redemption or is puttable). However,
the economic accrual rule will apply as of the effective date of the 1990 Act to the entire call premium on stock that
is callable solely at the option of the issuer (but not mandatorily redeemable or puttable) if such premium is considered
to be unreasonable under the current regulations. In such cases, except as provided in regulations, the entire call
premium will be accrued over the period of time during which the preferred stock cannot be called for redemption. It
should be noted that the committee reports also authorize the Secretary to treat stock that, in form, is merely callable
as being subject to a mandatory redemption or a put if the existence of other arrangements effectively requires the
issuer to redeem the stock. H.R. Conf. Rep. No. 964, 101st Cong., 2d Sess. 1095 (1990). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Comments invited. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The IRS and Treasury invite public comment on the proposed regulations and on any issues involving the implementation
of the 1990 Act amendments to section 305(c), including the extent to which OID principles should be adopted in the
section 305(c) context and the appropriate treatment of unpaid cumulative dividends. 
